Env.Page.Title = NAT

Env.Help.Text = In the <b>port forwarding</b> section, you can define the destination among your equipments for traffic coming from the Internet. Some software need to be reached directly from the Internet in order to function properly (games, peer to peer,...). You can configure these rules here. Check the documentation coming with the software for more information.<br /><br />In the <b>UPnP</b> section, you can disable or enable the UPnP service of your Box. When UPnP is enabled, you don't need to configure rules for address translation for UPnP compatible software.<br /><br />In the <b>DMZ</b> section, you can enable or disable the DMZ feature of the Box. When the DMZ is enabled, you can allow one of your devices to be accessible from the Internet. It is recommended that you use a firewall on this device.<br /><br />In the <b>Proxy Wake on LAN</b> section, you can enable or disable the Proxy Wake on LAN feature of the Box. When service is enabled, you can send WoL packets from the Internet to a device located in the LAN of the Box.<br/><br />In the <b>ALGs</b> section, you can enable or disable the ALGs features of the Box. If you are using an external VoIP service, you may need to disable SIP ALG.

